{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-b388abc15b90e034", "type": "tool_result", "content": "=== 2603.23810 ===\narxiv_id: '2603.23810'\ntitle: Rethinking Masking Strategies for Masked Prediction-based Audio Self-supervised\n  Learning\nauthors:\n- Daisuke Niizumi\n- Daiki Takeuchi\n- Masahiro Yasuda\n- Binh Thien Nguyen\n- Noboru Harada\n- Nobutaka Ono\nyear: 2026\nvenue: ''\ncategories:\n- eess.AS\n- cs.MM\n- cs.SD\ntopic: speech_representation\ntags:\n- SSL\n- SSL/预测式-离散\ncontributions:\n- We clarify the impact of masking strategies on audio spectrogram-based representation\n  learning, highlighting their effects across different downstream tasks.\n- We propose DWM, a lightweight masking strategy tailored to audio spectrograms, which\n  leverages dispersion patterns with minimal additional computational cost.\n=== 2605.14231 ===\narxiv_id: '2605.14231'\ntitle: 'AudioMosaic: Contrastive Masked Audio Representation Learning'\nauthors:\n- Hanxun Huang\n- Qizhou Wang\n- Xingjun Ma\n- Cihang Xie\n- Christopher Leckie\n- Sarah Erfani\nyear: 2026\nvenue: ''\ncategories:\n- cs.LG\n- cs.AI\n- cs.SD\ntopic: ''\ntags:\n- SSL\n- SSL/对比式\ncontributions:\n- AudioMosaic introduces a contrastive audio pre-training framework that uses structured\n  time-frequency masking to construct complementary positive pairs for effective and\n  efficient spectrogram-based learning.\n- A representation-level analysis using effective rank demonstrates that structured\n  time-frequency masking prevents dimension collapse by reducing shared local redundancy", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "db0a2bcd-9a0f-4744-b7a0-e57185ed69ed", "uuid": "3d18f3f9-1b8a-490a-bd2c-78ac703241d9", "timestamp": "2026-07-06T07:55:40.189Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "=== 2603.23810 ===\narxiv_id: '2603.23810'\ntitle: Rethinking Masking Strategies for Masked Prediction-based Audio Self-supervised\n  Learning\nauthors:\n- Daisuke Niizumi