{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a9f26c4dfba4750b", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\t                                                                                                                                                                                               1\n2\t\n3\t\n4\t\n5\t\n6\t                                                   From Objectives to Applications: Aligning\n7\t                                                  Architectural Biases in Audio Self-Supervised\n8\t                                                                     Learning\n9\t                                           Kele Xu, Yulu Fang, Boda Zhou, Yulin Sun, Qisheng Xu, Qiya Song, Jin Zhang, Cheng Yang, Huaimin Wang\n10\t\n11\t\n12\t\n13\t                                             Abstract—This paper examines audio self-supervised learning\n14\t                                          (SSL) through the alignment between pretraining objectives,\n15\t                                          architectural inductive biases, and downstream applications.\n16\tarXiv:2607.00387v1 [eess.AS] 1 Jul 2026\n17\t\n18\t\n19\t\n20\t\n21\t                                          Rather than treating SSL methods as a chronological sequence\n22\t                                          of pretext tasks or model families, we ask how different su-\n23\t                                          pervisory signals shape the representations that models are\n24\t                                          expected to learn. The discussion is organized around five\n25\t                                          paradigms: auxiliary tasks, contrastive learning, generative re-\n26\t                                          construction, discrete token prediction, and multimodal align-\n27\t                                          ment. These objectives place different demands on the model,\n28\t                                          from local structural sensitivity and contrastive invariance to\n29\t                                          contextual inference, discrete semantic abstraction, and multi-\n30\t                                          modal grounding. We relate these demands to the biases of\n31\t                                          CNNs, recurrent and State Space Models, Transformers, and\n32\t                                          hybrid architectures, showing how local acoustic compression,\n33\t                                          sequential state propagation, content-dependent global routing,\n34\t                                          and local–global integration support different forms of audio\n35\t                                          SSL. The same view is then used to interpret downstream\n36\t                                          applications in speech processing, environmental sound analy-            Fig. 1. Evolution of research activity in self-supervised audio representation\n37\t                                          sis, music information retrieval, medical and bioacoustic anal-          learning. Annual publication counts indicate the growing scholarly attention\n38\t                                                                                                                   to audio SSL, with a marked increase in recent years.\n39\t                                          ysis, and multimodal audio understanding as practical tests\n40\t                                          of whether learned representations and architectural choices\n41\t                                          generalize across domains. We also review benchmark protocols\n42\t                                          and open challenges, including tokenization bottlenecks, long-           data are increasingly abundant across real-world scenarios.\n43\t                                          context efficiency, robustness, and secure multimodal deployment,        This imbalance between scarce annotations and abundant raw\n44\t                                          and discuss how codec-based tokenization and audio-language              audio has made self-supervised learning (SSL) a compelling\n45\t                                          modeling extend this objective–architecture–application pipeline.        paradigm for audio representation learning, enabling models\n46\t                                          The accompanying repository is released at https://github.com/\n47\t                                          colaudiolab/Awesome-Self-Supervised-Audio-Learning.                      to exploit unlabeled data and improve transferability across\n48\t                                                                                                                   downstream tasks. As shown in Fig. 1, annual publication\n49\t                                             Index Terms—Audio Signal Processing, Self-Supervised Learn-           counts suggest a rapid increase in research activity related to\n50\t                                          ing, Large Audio Language Models, Multimodal Alignment.\n51\t                                                                                                                   audio SSL.\n52\t                                                                                                                      Beyond the annotation bottleneck, supervised audio learn-\n53\t                                                                  I. I NTRODUCTION                                 ing also faces limitations in generalization and robustness.\n54\t                                                                                                                   Models trained with predefined labels may rely on dataset-\n55\t                                          D     EEP supervised learning has substantially advanced au-\n56\t                                                dio signal processing [1]–[3]. However, its success is\n57\t                                          largely predicated on the availability of large-scale labeled\n58\t                                                                                                                   specific shortcuts or spurious correlations rather than learning\n59\t                                                                                                                   the underlying acoustic structures, leading to performance\n60\t                                                                                                                   degradation under domain shifts, noisy recording conditions,\n61\t                                          datasets [4]. In specialized audio domains, constructing such\n62\t                                                                                                                   or adversarial perturbations [9]–[11]. SSL addresses these\n63\t                                          datasets is often prohibitively expensive and time-consuming,\n64\t                                                                                                                   limitations by deriving supervisory signals from the intrinsic\n65\t                                          since annotation typically requires domain expertise, careful\n66\t                                                                                                                   structure of audio signals rather than from manual annotations.\n67\t                                          quality control, and repeated verification. Manual labeling may\n68\t                                                                                                                   In doing so, it encourages models to capture latent temporal,\n69\t                                          also introduce annotation bias and privacy risks, particularly\n70\t                                                                                                                   spectral, and contextual regularities from raw audio. Such\n71\t                                          when recordings contain sensitive acoustic information. For\n72\t                                                                                                                   supervision is typically instantiated through carefully designed\n73\t                                          instance, medical audio analysis requires trained healthcare\n74\t                                                                                                                   proxy or pretext tasks, which define the learning objectives\n75\t                                          professionals to annotate heart sounds or respiratory sig-\n76\t                                                                                                                   used to extract general-purpose acoustic representations from\n77\t                                          nals [5], [6], while environmental sound analysis often relies\n78\t                                                                                                                   unlabeled audio.\n79\t                                          on expert knowledge to identify specific acoustic events from\n80\t                                                                                                                      Building on this principle, audio SSL methods differ pri-\n81\t                                          long-duration recordings [7], [8]. By contrast, unlabeled audio\n82\t                                                                                                                   marily in how they formulate pretext tasks and derive train-\n83\t                                            Corresponding authors: Yunlin Sun (sunyulin@nudt.edu.cn) and Qisheng 