 inductive biases, and downstream applications.\narXiv:2607.00387v1 [eess.AS] 1 Jul 2026\n\n\n\n\n                                          Rather than treating SSL methods as a chronological sequence\n                                          of pretext tasks or model families, we ask how different su-\n                                          pervisory signals shape the representations that models are\n                                          expected to learn. The discussion is organized around five\n                                          paradigms: auxiliary tasks, contrastive learning, generative re-\n                                          construction, discrete token prediction, and multimodal align-\n                                          ment. These objectives place different demands on the model,\n                                          from local structural sensitivity and contrastive invariance to\n                                          contextual inference, discrete semantic abstraction, and multi-\n                                          modal grounding. We relate these demands to the biases of\n                                          CNNs, recurrent and State Space Models, Transformers, and\n                                          hybrid architectures, showing how local acoustic compression,\n                                          sequential state propagation, content-dependent global routing,\n                                          and local–global integration support different forms of audio\n                                          SSL. The same view is then used to interpret downstream\n                                          applications in speech processing, environmental sound analy-            Fig. 1. Evolution of research activity in self-supervised audio representation\n                                          sis, music information retrieval, medical and bioacoustic anal-          learning. Annual publication counts indicate the growing scholarly attention\n                                                                                                                   to audio SSL, with a marked increase in recent years.\n                                          ysis, and multimodal audio understanding as practical tests\n                                          of whether learned representations and architectural choices\n                                          generalize across domains. We also review benchmark protocols\n                                          and open challenges, including tokenization bottlenecks, long-           data are increasingly abundant across real-world scenarios.\n                                          context efficiency, robustness, and secure multimodal deployment,        This imbalance between scarce annotations and abundant raw\n                                          and discuss how codec-based tokenization and audio-language              audio has made self-supervised learning (SSL) a compelling\n                                          modeling extend this objective–architecture–application pipeline.        paradigm for audio representation learning, enabling models\n                                          The accompanying repository is released at https://github.com/\n                                          colaudiolab/Awesome-Self-Supervised-Audio-Learning.                      to exploit unlabeled data and improve transferability across\n                                                                                                                   downstream tasks. As shown in Fig. 1, annual publication\n                                             Index Terms—Audio Signal Processing, Self-Supervised Learn-           counts suggest a rapid increase in research activity related to\n                                          ing, Large Audio Language Models, Multimodal Alignment.\n                                